- **Flask route restrictions**: Framework-level method filtering provides additional safety net
- **Generic error messages**: Don't reveal internal permission structure to attackers

Your authorization check may be vulnerable to HTTP verb tampering. If you only check authorization on specific HTTP methods, attackers can bypass controls by using unexpected verbs.

**VULNERABLE CODE**:

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

// Middleware that only checks admin role for specific methods
function checkAdminAccess(req, res, next) {
  // VULNERABLE: Only checks POST and DELETE methods
  if (req.method === 'POST' || req.method === 'DELETE') {
    if (!req.user || req.user.role !== 'admin') {
      return res.status(403).json({ error: 'Admin access required' });
    }
  }
  next();
}

app.use('/api/admin', checkAdminAccess);

// Admin user management endpoint
app.all('/api/admin/users/:id', (req, res) => {
  const userId = req.params.id;

  if (req.method === 'GET') {
    // Fetch user details - should be admin only!
    return res.json(getUserDetails(userId));
  }

  if (req.method === 'DELETE') {
    deleteUser(userId);
    return res.json({ success: true });
  }

  // VULNERABLE: PATCH method not explicitly handled but executes
  if (req.body.role) {
    updateUserRole(userId, req.body.role);
    return res.json({ success: true });
  }

  res.status(405).json({ error: 'Method not allowed' });
});

app.listen(3000);
```

**Attack Payload**:
```bash
# Bypass admin check using HEAD method to probe sensitive endpoints
curl -X HEAD http://example.com/api/admin/users/1 -H "Cookie: session=user_token"

# Use PATCH to modify user roles without admin authorization
curl -X PATCH http://example.com/api/admin/users/1 \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -H "Cookie: session=regular_user_token" \
  -d '{"role": "admin"}'

# Use OPTIONS to enumerate available endpoints
curl -X OPTIONS http://example.com/api/admin/users/1
```

**Why This Is Dangerous**:
- Authorization middleware only validates POST and DELETE methods
- Attackers can use GET, PATCH, PUT, HEAD, or OPTIONS to bypass checks
- `app.all()` accepts any HTTP verb, creating attack surface
- Missing method-specific authorization allows privilege escalation

**SECURE VERSION**:

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

// Secure middleware that checks ALL requests to admin routes
